Balancing Cost of Living with SanFrancisco Pay Scales¶

df1 <- read.csv("/content/employee-compensation.csv")

1) Objective of the Proposed Research:¶

  • The primary objective of the research is to comprehensively analyze the key factors influencing the cost of living in the city, with a specific focus on income. The dataset consists of data related to company, departments, salaries and benefits which gives us a glimpse about the job scenario in San Francisco. With the help of this thorough analysis, the research aims to provide valuable insights into the complex economic dynamics that shape the lives of San Francisco residents.

  • Firstly, the research seeks to provide a clear and data-driven understanding of income trends in San Francisco. This includes examining median household incomes, income disparities, and the influence of major employment sectors on income levels. This thorough examination will allow readers to grasp the economic diversity within the city and comprehend the financial challenges faced by various segments of the population.

  • Secondly, the research aims to uncover how fifferent jobs types correlate with retirement, health,dental and other benefits that affect the essential living expenses in San Francisco. Additionally, the report will delve into the relationship between the departmenOrganization Group, department, Job Family and their respective compensation benefits it offers to its employees inorder to secure their future.
  • Lastly, the objective of this research is to equip San Francisco Chronicle newspaper with actionable insights into the income dynamics of San Francisco. By presenting a comprehensive and data-driven view of income-related issues, the research serves as a vital tool for informed decision-making for the readers of the San Francisco Chronicle.

  • Organization.Group - This column gives us details about the organisation group as whole under which there are various departments.

  • Year - This column provides us details about the year and used in filtering data from the type of year. Its range is from 2013 to 2020.

  • Year.Type - This column type provides us with the two types of year which are Fiscal and Calendar. Using 2015 as an example, Fiscal Year 2015 covers the period from July 2014 to June 2015 and Calendar Year 2015 covers the period from January 2015 to December 2015. We will consider Fiscal year for our analysis as hiring, financial and all other statistics for a company are based on fiscal year.

  • Department - This column provides us details about various departments that fall under the organization umbrella. We would use this column to predict which department offers higher and lower salaries.

  • Job - This column provides us with detailed information about the designation of the employee. This can also provide us with the salary range within a particular job role for a fresher and experienced employee and their growth potential.

  • Total.Salary - This column consists of sum of Salary + Overtime + Other benefits from the main dataframe. We weill use this as our primary data to predict various patterns in paygrades among companies.

  • Retirement - This column describes city contributions to employee retirement plans. We will use this column data to describe which job has more security as compared to others.

  • Total Benefits - This column is Retirement + Health&Dental Benefits + Other Benefits. It describes the total benefits that a company offers to an employee interms of health, retirement and other benefits.

# Calculating the Lowest Average compensation for top 5 jobs
Lowest_Compensation <- df1[c('Year','Year.Type','Job','Job.Family','Total.Compensation')]

Lowest_Compensation <- Lowest_Compensation[Lowest_Compensation$Year.Type %in% c('Fiscal'),]
Lowest_Compensation <- Lowest_Compensation[Lowest_Compensation$Year %in% c('2020'),]

Lowest_Compensation$Total.Compensation <- as.numeric(Lowest_Compensation$Total.Compensation)

#Now calculate the lowest compensation averaging Total Compensation

#Removing Job titles with unknown Job Family
Lowest_Compensation_Average <- Lowest_Compensation_Average[Lowest_Compensation_Average$Job.Family != 'Untitled', ]
Lowest_Compensation_Average <- Lowest_Compensation_Average[Lowest_Compensation_Average$Job.Family != 'Unassigned', ]

# Initialize an empty vector to store the results
average_salaries <- numeric()

# Get unique years in the dataset
unique_years <- unique(df2$Year)

# Loop through each unique year
for (year in unique_years) {
  # Subset the dataframe for the current year
  year_data <- df2[df2$Year == year, ]

  # Calculate the mean of "Total.Salary" for the current year
  mean_salary <- mean(year_data$Total.Salary, na.rm = TRUE)

  # Append the result to the vector
  average_salaries <- c(average_salaries, mean_salary)
}

# Create a data frame with year and average salary
result <- data.frame(Year = unique_years, Average_Salary = average_salaries)

# Print the results
print(result)

#Loop 2
C
# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
lowest_avg_salaries_2020 <- data.frame(Department = character(), Average_Salary = numeric())

# Get unique departments in the dataset
unique_departments <- unique(df2$Department)

# Filter the data for the year 2020
data_2020 <- df2[df2$Year == 2020, ]

# Loop through each unique department
for (department in unique_departments) {
  # Subset the data for the current department
  department_data <- data_2020[data_2020$Department == department, ]

  # Calculate the average salary for the current department
  avg_salary <- mean(department_data$Total.Salary, na.rm = TRUE)

  # Create a new row for the results
  result_row <- data.frame(Department = department, Average_Salary = avg_salary)

  # Append the result row to the lowest_avg_salaries_2020 data frame
  lowest_avg_salaries_2020 <- rbind(lowest_avg_salaries_2020, result_row)
}

# Sort the data frame by average salary in ascending order
lowest_avg_salaries_2020 <- lowest_avg_salaries_2020[order(lowest_avg_salaries_2020$Average_Salary), ]

# Get the top 10 departments with the lowest average salaries
top_10_lowest_avg_salaries <- head(lowest_avg_salaries_2020, 10)

# Print the top 10 departments

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
top_10_avg_salaries_by_job_family <- data.frame(Job_Family = character(), Average_Salary = numeric())

# Loop through each unique job family
for (job_family in unique_job_families) {
  # Subset the data for the current job family
  job_family_data <- df2[df2$Job.Family == job_family, ]

  # Calculate the average salary for the current job family
  avg_salary <- mean(job_family_data$Total.Salary, na.rm = TRUE)

  # Create a new row for the results
  result_row <- data.frame(Job_Family = job_family, Average_Salary = avg_salary)

  # Append the result row to the data frame
  top_10_avg_salaries_by_job_family <- rbind(top_10_avg_salaries_by_job_family, result_row)
}

# Sort the data frame by average salary in descending order

8) Summary¶

Employment Insights: List 1 highlights the top five organization groups that contributed the most to employment in San Francisco in 2020. Notably, the "Community Health" and "Culture & Recreation" groups lead the pack, showcasing the significance of these sectors in the local job market. On the contrary, the "General City Responsibilities" group provides the fewest employment opportunities, indicating its limited presence compared to others.

Salary and Compensation Trends (Lists 2 and 5): Lists 2 and 5 provide insights into the compensation landscape. List 2 identifies the ten job titles with the lowest salaries, spanning roles like library pages and public service aides, which tend to offer lower compensation. Meanwhile, List 5 examines the lowest average total compensation from 2013 to 2020, highlighting positions like "Diagnostic Imaging Tech IV" and "Camp Assistant" as consistently lower-paying roles, underscoring potential disparities in earnings within the dataset.

Benefits and Job Security (List 3): List 3 focuses on job titles with limited benefits, with specific attention to negative retirement benefits. For instance, it points out that job titles related to nursing, despite being in the "Community Health" organization group, exhibit negative retirement benefits, which may raise concerns about job security for individuals in these roles.

Union Influence (List 4): List 4 analyzes the prevalence of unions within job family types. Notably, job families such as "Nursing" and "Police Services" have a significant union presence, indicating potential job security and collective bargaining advantages for employees in these fields.

Salary Trends Over the Years: The visualization of average salaries per year illustrates the evolution of compensation levels in San Francisco from 2013 to 2020. It's evident that average salaries remained relatively stable until 2016, after which they exhibited a gradual increase, with 2020 recording the highest average salaries.

Departmental Disparities: The provided data highlights departmental disparities in salaries. Some departments, like "Registrar," "Recreation and Park Commission," and "Board of Appeals," offer notably lower average salaries, while others, like "Administrative & Mgmt (Unrep)" and "Fire Services," provide considerably higher average salaries, showcasing variations in earning potential across departments.

In summary, the content offers comprehensive insights into San Francisco's job market, including employment trends, salary disparities, benefits, and the impact of unions on job security. These findings provide valuable information for individuals seeking employment in the area and shed light on critical aspects of compensation and employment dynamics in the region.

9) Recommendations¶

Career Choices: Consider career options within sectors like "Community Health" and "Culture & Recreation," which offer higher employment opportunities. Conversely, exercise caution when opting for roles with consistently lower salaries and limited benefits, as seen in positions like "Diagnostic Imaging Tech IV."

Union Membership: Jobs in job families with significant union representation, such as "Nursing" and "Police Services," may offer better job security and potential bargaining power. Explore opportunities in these fields for added employment stability.

Salary Trends: Be aware of salary trends over the years. While recent years have seen salary increases, it's essential to stay informed about changing compensation levels to make informed career decisions.

Departmental Disparities: When considering employment in specific departments, factor in salary disparities. Departments like "Administrative & Mgmt (Unrep)" and "Fire Services" tend to offer higher salaries, while others may provide lower earning potential.

Benefits Assessment: Examine benefits packages carefully, especially retirement benefits. Jobs with negative retirement benefits, like certain nursing positions, may indicate potential job security concerns after retirement.

Incorporating these considerations into career decisions can help individuals make informed choices and navigate the San Francisco job market effectively.
